node.text:
It’s official: Today’s the day ... Our 50th anniversary! 
NOAA was “born” Oct. 3, 1970, and we’ve never felt more ready to face the next 50 yrs. Join us as we look back at some of our proudest moments.
For all of our accomplishments on behalf of the nation, we are deeply grateful to the hardworking and passionate NOAA workforce, without whom our achievements as one of the federal government’s three science agencies would not have been possible -- or successful.
(*Captioned video at: https://youtu.be/5hVukYLG5m4. 
You can also watch at https://www.noaa.gov/noaa-50th-home )

node.text:
We don’t like to talk about ourselves too much ... So we’ll let our awesome partners and colleagues do it instead! (See some familiar faces?) Thank you all for your best wishes on our 50th Anniversary! 

[Captioned video: https://www.noaa.gov/heritage/video/noaa-50th-anniversary-message-from-our-partners …]

#NOAAAt50  #50YearsOfNOAA

node.text:
A crab on a weather satellite? A turtle flying a hurricane hunter plane? These aquatic friends from Jim Toomey’s comic strip, Sherman’s Lagoon, took a NOAA-themed adventure for NOAA’s 50th. Story at: https://www.noaa.gov/heritage/stories/sherman-s-lagoon-friends-go-on-noaa-themed-adventure

[Captioned video at https://youtu.be/OfhxK87DiI4] #NOAAat50

node.title: Cartoonist Jim Toomey and Sherman’s Lagoon celebrate NOAA’s 50th

node.text:
You don’t make it to 50 years of science, service and stewardship without great people. Perhaps @NOAA staff members say it best. 

A heartfelt thank you to our NOAA workforce for expertly and passionately serving the American people.

(Captioned video at: https://youtu.be/OfhxK87DiI4 and https://www.noaa.gov/heritage/video/video-50-years-of-science-service-and-stewardship )

node.text:
Just in: NOAA forecasters maintain their *above-average* hurricane season
prediction for the Atlantic Basin, as the peak months are now underway.

Today, we released our *update* to the 2021 Atlantic #HurricaneSeason
Outlook issued in May: https://bit.ly/AtlHurricaneSeasonUpdate2021

NOAA forecasters have updated their Atlantic #HurricaneSeason prediction to:

-- 15-21 named storms, of which 7-10 could become hurricanes … including
3-5 “major” hurricanes.

The 2021 Atlantic hurricane season has been off to a record setting start,
with Hurricane #Elsa becoming the earliest 5th named storm on record.

For late-breaking hurricane watches and warnings this season:

-- Bookmark www.hurricanes.gov and www.weather.gov

-- Follow NOAA’s National Hurricane Center on Twitter at @NHC_Atlantic and
NOAA's U.S. National Weather Service at @NWS

-- Visit Ready.gov for tips on how to prepare for hurricane season

#nature #science #hurricanes #Atlantic  #HurricaneSeason #HurricaneOutlook
#itonlytakesone

node.text:
Cuteness alert!

It's #WorldSeaTurtleDay ... and it falls smack in the middle of @NOAAFisheries #SeaTurtleWeek! 

In this photo, a freshly hatched pair of green sea turtles, or honu in Hawaiian, make their way to the ocean in the Northwestern Hawaiian Islands, on a beach along #Papahānaumokuākea Marine National Monument -- which has just celebrated 15 years as a marine monument! (Photo credit: Mark Sullivan/NOAA.) 

Sea turtles have been swimming in Earth’s oceans for hundreds of millions of years. These marine reptiles lead incredible lives, surviving for many decades at sea, traveling thousands of miles in search of food and eventually, returning to the beaches where they were born to nest.

--> See how we're helping to protect 6 species of sea turtles found in U.S. waters: www.fisheries.noaa.gov/feature-story/sea-turtle-week-2021

[About the Monument: The name Papahānaumokuākea commemorates the union of two Hawaiian ancestors – Papahānaumoku and Wākea – who gave rise to the Hawaiian Archipelago, the taro plant, and the Hawaiian people. 

Papahānaumokuākea Marine National Monument is the largest contiguous fully protected conservation area under the U.S. flag and one of the largest marine conservation areas in the world. It encompasses 582,578 square miles of the Pacific Ocean (1,508,870 square kilometers) -- an area larger than all the of country's national parks combined. Learn more at https://www.papahanaumokuakea.gov/ and sanctuaries.noaa.gov]

#nature #science #SeaTurtles #GreenSeaTurtles #Hawaii #HawaiianIslands #MarineMonument @Sanctuaries

node.text:
It’s getting to be that time of year again …

Forecasters at the NOAA NWS Climate Prediction Center predict another “active”, above-normal #Atlantic #HurricaneSeason for 2021, but they do not anticipate the historic level of storm activity seen in 2020.

NOAA predicts a likely range of 13-20 named storms, of which 6-10 could become hurricanes -- including 3-5 major hurricanes. 

Forecasters provide these ranges with a 70% confidence.

**Atlantic hurricane season starts June 1, so PREPARE NOW.

Get tips and resources at: www.ready.gov/hurricanes

-->For late-breaking Atlantic hurricane watches and warnings this season, bookmark hurricanes.gov, hurricanes.gov/mobile, mobile.weather.gov

--> Follow the NOAA's National Hurricane Center on Twitter at @NHC_Atlantic and NOAA's National Weather Service at @NWS.

#nature #science #hurricanes #HurricaneSeason #TropicalCyclones #HurricaneOutlook #weather

node.text:
Happy #EarthDay2021, everyone!

Take some time to rediscover and connect with nature -- and help preserve the natural world in your neighborhood.

We have some great ideas and cool Earth-science content to get you started: http://bit.ly/NOAAEarthDay2021

About this photo: Early morning rainbow along the south shore of Maui taken on July 29, 2019 in the Hawaiian Islands Humpback Whale National Marine Sanctuary. Credit: Jeff Moore/NOAA.

+ Get more Earth Day stories, photos and video from all around NOAA this week! Find our major social media channels at: www.noaa.gov/stay-connected.

#nature #science #EarthDay #EarthDayNOAA #CitizenScience

We’re just 2 days away from Earth Day, April 22: 

Join us on noaa.gov & NOAA social channels for #EarthDayNOAA content & news you can use to positively impact the natural world in your own community.

—> Here are 10 ways we can all make a difference right now: 
https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/ocean/earthday.html

via @NOAAOcean

#nature #science #Earth #earthday #earthdayeveryday

Great news to share this Earth Week:

NOAA and our partners are beginning a 3-year effort to outplant more than 60,000 fragments of nursery-raised coral at Eastern Dry Rocks Sanctuary Preservation Area off the coast of Key West, Florida. 

This is the first large-scale endeavor dedicated to "Mission: Iconic Reefs," an unprecedented effort to restore 7 coral reefs within Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary (@floridakeysnoaagov on Facebook).

-->See our news release at: http://bit.ly/NOAAIconicReefs

In these 2 photos, staghorn coral fragments are attached to the reef with epoxy and tagged to keep track of genetic information. (Credit: @CoralRestorationFoundation)

#science #nature #coral #CoralReef #IconicReefs @NOAASanctuaries @NOAAocean #FloridaKeys #EarthDayNOAA #EveryDayIsEarthDay

node.text:
Spring may be springing here in the Northern Hemisphere ... but for scientists stationed at the South Pole, the long polar night is setting in.

LTJG Tim Holland, a NOAA Corps officer stationed at the South Pole, and NOAA scientist Joseph Samaniego will be working hard all winter operating the NOAA Global Monitoring Laboratory's instruments at the Atmospheric
Research Observatory -- that's the building pictured here as the sun was setting on March 13, 2021.

Throughout the winter, they'll be collecting and analyzing air samples and launching balloons fitted with instruments to measure ozone. 

Though the winter is dark, Tim, Joseph and the rest of the scientists and staff at the South Pole will be treated to bright stars and spectacular displays of
the Southern Lights.

Photo: LTJG Tim Holland/NOAA/ @NOAACorps.

#science #scientists #nature #SouthPole #sunset #winter #ozone #research @noaaresearch
